     <int-org-section id="CE.IO.580" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Activities</heading>
          <p>With a view to harmonizing national laws and pooling certain resources and facilities, the Council of Europe has concluded a number of conventions and agreements on European co-operation. From 1989 the Council undertook to increase engagement with all countries of the former Eastern bloc and to facilitate their accession to the organization. The first summit meeting was convened in October 1993, in Vienna, Austria. In October 1997 heads of state or of government met for the second time, in Strasbourg, France, with the aim of formulating a new social model to consolidate democracy throughout Europe. The third summit meeting, held in Warsaw, Poland, in May 2005, issued a Final Declaration and an Action Plan, which defined the principal tasks of the Council over the coming years as promoting human rights and the rule of law; strengthening the security of European citizens; and fostering co-operation with other international and European organizations.</p>
          <p-group>
               <heading>Reykjavík Summit</heading>
               <p>In accordance with a decision taken in November 2022 by the Committee of Ministers (based on a recent recommendation by a High Level Reflection Group), the Fourth Summit of Heads of State and Government was convened in May 2023, in Reykjavík, Iceland, on the theme `United around our values’, to address Russia’s war against Ukraine and the future priorities and direction of the Council’s work. The leaders adopted the Reykjavík Declaration, in which they emphasized that the organization had been founded as a peace project in the aftermath of the Second World War—an agenda that was now being challenged by Russia’s aggression against Ukraine—and reaffirmed commitment to developing mutual understanding among the peoples of Europe and to the Council of Europe’s values and its principles. The meeting adopted an Enlarged Partial Agreement on the Register of Damage for Ukraine; endorsed a series of Reykjavík Principles for Democracy; recommitted to the ECHR as the cornerstone of the organization’s protection framework; and stressed the constructive role of the Council of Europe in environmental protection, environmentally friendly landscape management, and public health.</p>
          </p-group>
          <!--Committee of Ministers, PACE-->
          <!--~Programme of Action against Corruption ~next summit of heads of state and government-->
          <p-group>
               <heading>Strategic Framework</heading>
               <p>In May 2021 the Committee of Ministers adopted a four-year Council of Europe strategic framework, which included the following objectives: promoting the accession of the European Union (EU) to the ECHR; supporting the long-term effectiveness of the ECHR system, with a particular focus on enhancing the implementation of judgments by the European Court of Human Rights; reviewing the efficiency of Council of Europe monitoring mechanisms; promoting civil society participation in Council of Europe activities; and reviewing the European Social Charter system. The Committee reiterated the importance of the Council of Europe’s standard-setting role in the context of digitalization and artificial intelligence (AI). The Council's activities have the following cross-cutting themes: children’s rights; democracy; intercultural dialogue; and combating violence.</p>
          </p-group>
          <p-group>
               <heading usage="ewyb edio eerca casee">Ukraine</heading>
               <p usage="eerca">
        The Committee of Ministers condemned the referendum conducted in mid-March 2014 by the Crimean authorities, in violation of Ukrainian legislation, and deplored Russia’s decision to grant admittance to the territory. In April the Committee of Ministers adopted a report issued by the Advisory Committee on the Framework Convention for National Minorities that stated deep concern over the safety and access to rights of minority populations in Crimea, with particular reference to individuals belonging to the Crimean Tatar and Ukrainian communities. In mid-July the Secretary-General condemned the alleged shooting down from airspace over eastern Ukraine of a Malaysia Airlines passenger flight (MH17), which had resulted in 298 fatalities, and urged that an international investigation should be conducted into the incident without delay. (In November 2022, following a trial in the Netherlands initiated by Dutch public prosecutors, two Russians and one Ukrainian separatist were found guilty, 
        <i>in absentia,</i>
        of murdering all of the plane’s passengers and crew and were sentenced to life terms of imprisonment; their arrests were ordered. In July 2020 the Netherlands Government had concluded that the Government of the Russian Federation should be tried at the European Court of Human Rights over its alleged role in the MH17 atrocity.)
      </p>
               <p usage="eerca">
        In May 2021 the Committee of Ministers urged Russia to release all unlawfully detained and convicted Ukrainian citizens, and to repeal decisions curtailing the functioning of the `Mejlis’ (legislature) of the Crimean Tatar minority, which had been accused by Russia of extremism and outlawed in April 2016. In June 2022, in response to a report issued in May by the Council’s Secretary-General on the 
        <publ-name>Human rights situation in the Autonomous Republic of Crimea and the City of Sevastopol,</publ-name>
         the Committee of Ministers stated great concern over alleged multiple grave violations of human rights and international humanitarian law being perpetrated under Russian rule. The Committee called for unrestricted access of Council of Europe bodies to the Crimean peninsula.
      </p>
               <p usage="ewyb edio eerca">In mid-February 2022 the Council of Europe’s Secretary-General, the Chairperson of the Committee of Ministers and President of PACE issued a joint statement in which they stated extreme concern at mounting tensions relating to a significant build-up of Russian military forces in the Russia-Ukraine border area. They urged the pursuit of constructive dialogue based on internationally accepted principles. On 21 February the Secretary-General condemned the recent formal recognition by Russia of the self-proclaimed `People’s Republics’ of Donetsk and Luhansk (eastern Ukraine) as being in violation of international law and as representing a breach of the Minsk Agreements (concluded, under OSCE auspices, in 2014-15 as a means of achieving a peaceful settlement of the conflict in Ukraine). On 22 February Russia’s President Vladimir Putin ordered that Russian forces should enter the disputed territories, and on 24 February Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine. Meeting on that day in extraordinary session the Committee of Ministers urged Russia immediately and unconditionally to halt its military operations in Ukraine, reiterating unwavering commitment to Ukraine’s sovereignty, independence and territorial integrity within its internationally recognized borders. On 25 February the Committee of Ministers suspended Russia’s rights of representation in both the Committee of Ministers and PACE (only Armenia opposed the suspension). The Committee of Ministers determined to co-operate closely with PACE in monitoring the situation and assessing the necessary consequences of Russia’s actions. On 16 March, in accordance with an Opinion adopted by PACE on the previous day, the Committee rescinded Russia’s membership of the Council and of its various partial agreements, with immediate effect.</p>
               <p usage="ewyb edio eerca">In early April 2022 the PACE General Rapporteur on Violence against Women denounced sexual violence allegedly being perpetrated against Ukrainians by Russian and affiliated troops, emphasizing that murder, pillage, torture and rape were being deployed as weaponry to attempt to destroy homes, families, people and morale in Ukraine. At that time the PACE President stated horror at reports that civilians were being killed by Russian forces withdrawing from Bucha and other settlements in the vicinity of the Ukrainian capital Kyiv. The Council of Europe Secretary-General also expressed her shock at ongoing events in Ukraine and called for a full investigation, and for accountability for the perpetrators.</p>
               <p usage="ewyb edio eerca">The Council was represented at the Ministerial Ukraine Accountability Conference that was convened in The Hague, Netherlands, in July 2022, by the Netherlands Government, International Criminal Court Prosecutor and EU Commissioner for Justice. In August the Council’s Secretary-General participated in the second summit (held online) of the Crimea Platform, a consultation format that was initiated in August 2021 to consolidate international policy aimed at reinstating Ukrainian control of Crimea. At the end of September 2022 the Secretary-General, the Chairperson of the Committee of Ministers and the President of PACE issued a statement that strongly condemned a decision by Russia to annex occupied Ukrainian territory, in violation of international law. In October PACE adopted a resolution that condemned Russia’s attempted annexation of areas of eastern Ukraine as an `affront to international law’.</p>
               <p usage="ewyb edio eerca">In December 2022 the Committee of Ministers adopted a €50m. Resilience, Recover and Reconstruction action plan for Ukraine, to cover the period 2023-26. This aimed to enhance Ukraine’s public institutions by strengthening the rule of law, democratic governance and the protection of citizens’ human rights. The Council was also to support Ukraine in meeting the requirements of its EU membership candidacy (candidate status having been granted by the European Council in June 2022).</p>
               <p>In early May 2023 the Council of Europe’s Secretary-General participated in an online summit of the leaders of the (37) member states of the coalition aiming to create a Special Tribunal on the Crime of Aggression against Ukraine. (The Council of Europe also supports the Office of the Prosecutor of the International Criminal Court in its investigations into war crimes and gross human rights violations committed by Russia.) In mid-May the Council of Europe summit meeting adopted an Enlarged Partial Agreement on the Register of Damage for Ukraine, with 41 signatories, including non-member (observers) Canada, Japan, Mexico and the USA, as well as the EU. The Register was to detail evidence and claims information relating to damage, loss or injury caused by Russia's aggression since 24 February 2022 against affected individuals and the state of Ukraine, and was envisaged as a basis for the eventual establishment of an international comprehensive compensation mechanism (to be paid for by Russia). A Declaration on the situation of children in Ukraine was also issued. The first constitutive meeting of the Conference of Participants of the Register was convened in late June 2023. On 10 September the Secretary-General, President of the Committee of Ministers and PACE President issued a joint statement that strongly condemned illegitimate local elections that had just been conducted in Russian-occupied Donetsk, Kherson, Luhansk and Zaporizhzhya. In April 2024 PACE recommended that frozen Russian state assets should be seized and used in support of the reconstruction of Ukraine.</p>
          </p-group>
          <int-org-section id="CE.IO.581" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Protecting and Promoting Human Rights</heading>
               <p>The protection of human rights is one of the Council of Europe’s core goals, to be achieved in four main areas: the effective supervision and protection of fundamental rights and freedoms; the identification of new threats to human rights and human dignity; the development of public awareness of the importance of human rights; and the promotion of human rights education and professional training.</p>
               <p>The Steering Committee for Human Rights, responsible for intergovernmental co-operation in the field of human rights and fundamental freedoms, has been responsible for the elaboration of several conventions and other legal instruments. The most significant treaties in this area include the ECHR; the European Social Charter; the European Convention for the Prevention of Torture and Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment; the Framework Convention for the Protection of National Minorities; the European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages; the Convention on Action against Trafficking in Human Beings; and the Convention on Access to Official Documents.</p>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>European Convention on Human Rights</heading>
                    <p>
          The ECHR was adopted in 1950 and entered into force in 1953. In 1959 the European Court of Human Rights was established, with compulsory jurisdiction, and competence to consider complaints lodged by states parties to the Convention and by individuals, groups of individuals or NGOs claiming to be victims of breaches of the Convention's guarantees. Protocols to the ECHR include: No. 12, which entered into force in April 2005, enforcing a general prohibition of discrimination; No. 13, which entered into force in July 2003, guaranteeing the abolition of the death penalty in all circumstances, including in time of war; No. 15, which entered into force on 1 August 2021, and emphasized states’ margin of appreciation in applying the Convention, and the subsidiarity of the Convention to the safeguarding of human rights at national level; and No. 16, which entered into force on 1 August 2018, allowing the highest courts and tribunals of a contracting party to request advisory opinions from the European Court of Human Rights on questions of principle relating to the interpretation or application of the rights and freedoms defined in the Convention and its protocols. In April 2018 Council of Europe ministers responsible for justice adopted the Copenhagen Declaration on reforming the Convention, with a focus on enhancing, 
          <i>inter alia,</i>
           shared responsibility; national compliance; interaction between national and European level; clarity and coherence in interpretation; and the enforcement of sentences. ECHR-KS, an online knowledge sharing platform, was launched in October 2022.
        </p>
                    <p>During a period of public emergency member states may suspend parts of the ECHR. The derogation of the following provisions is, however, forbidden: Article 2 (on the right to life), Article 3 (on the prohibition of torture and inhumane or degrading treatment or punishment), Article 4, Paragraph 1 (on the prohibition of slavery), and Article 7 (on no punishment without law).</p>
                    <p usage="edio ewyb eerca">Ukraine suspended application of parts of the Convention in June 2015. In November of that year, in the aftermath of large-scale Islamist terrorist attacks against Paris, France, also suspended application of parts of the Convention. In July 2016, following an attempted coup, the Turkish authorities notified their intention of a similar suspension.</p>
                    <p usage="edio ewyb casee eerca">During March 2020 several member states declared states of emergency or assumed other emergency powers in order to combat the COVID-19 pandemic crisis. While many countries had declared formal states of emergency within the context of national constitutional provisions, some—reportedly Armenia, Estonia, Georgia, Latvia, Moldova and Romania—had, furthermore, informed the Council of Europe of their intention to invoke Article 15 of the ECHR, which permits derogation of parts of the Convention in `time of war or other public emergency threatening the life of the nation’.</p>
                    <p>During 2023 the Court delivered 6,931 judgments.</p>
                    <!--EU accession to ECHR 2020 Russia constitutional amendments passed stating it may ignore international legal decisions that violate its sovereignty-->
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>European Social Charter</heading>
                    <p>The European Social Charter, in force since 1965, is the counterpart of the ECHR in the field of protection of economic and social rights. A revised Charter, which amended existing guarantees and incorporated new rights, was opened for signature in May 1996, and entered into force on 1 July 1999. By January 2024 27 member states had ratified the Charter and 35 had ratified the revised Charter. Rights guaranteed by the Charter concern all individuals in their daily lives in matters of housing, health, education, employment, social protection, movement of persons and non-discrimination. A 15-member European Committee of Social Rights decides on the conformity of national situations with the Charter. It considers reports submitted annually by member states, and also considers collective complaints submitted in the framework of an Additional Protocol (1995), permitting trade unions, employers' organizations and NGOs to lodge complaints about alleged violations of the Charter. When a country does not bring a situation into conformity, the Committee of Ministers may, on the basis of decisions prepared by a Governmental Committee (composed of representatives of each Contracting Party), issue recommendations to the state concerned, inviting it to change its legislation or practice in accordance with the Charter’s requirements.</p>
                    <p>A High-Level Conference on the European Social Charter, convened by the Council of Europe in October 2014, in Turin, Italy, launched the Turin Process aimed at strengthening the Charter’s implementation. In February 2015 a follow up conference, convened in Brussels, under the Turin Process, issued the `Brussels Document’ addressing the future of the protection of social rights in Europe. An interparliamentary conference was held in March 2016 within the Turin Process framework. In May 2023 the fourth Summit of the Council of Europe agreed to consider the organization of a further High-Level Conference.</p>
                    <p>The European Code of Social Security and its Protocol entered into force in 1968. These instruments set minimum standards for medical care and the following benefits: sickness; old age; unemployment; employment injury; family; maternity; invalidity; and survivor's benefits. A revision of these instruments, aiming to provide higher standards and greater flexibility, was opened for signature in 1990; by January 2024 the revision had only been ratified by one member state (the Netherlands).</p>
                    <p usage="ewyb edio">The European Convention on Social Security, in force since 1977, currently applies in Austria, Belgium, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal, Spain and Türkiye; most of the provisions apply automatically, while others are subject to the conclusion of additional multilateral or bilateral agreements. The Convention is concerned with establishing the following four fundamental principles of international law on social security: equality of treatment; unity of applicable legislation; conservation of rights accrued or in the course of acquisition; and payment of benefits abroad. In 1994 a Protocol to the Convention, providing for the enlargement of the personal scope of the Convention, was opened for signature; by January 2024 it had been ratified only by Portugal (and required two ratifications to enter into force).</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Convention for the Prevention of Torture and Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment</heading>
                    <p>The 1987 Convention for the Prevention of Torture and Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment provided for the establishment of the European Committee for the Prevention of Torture and Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment (CPT), comprising independent experts who examine the treatment of persons deprived of their liberty with a view to strengthening, if necessary, protection from torture and from inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment. It conducts periodic visits to police stations, prisons, detention centres, and all other sites where persons are deprived of their liberty by a public authority, in all states parties to the Convention, and may also undertake ad hoc visits when the Committee considers them necessary. After each visit the CPT drafts a report of its findings and any further advice or recommendations, based on dialogue and co-operation. In March 2020 the CPT issued a statement urging governments to ensure that all persons deprived of their liberty were not subjected to degrading treatment in the context of measures taken to contain the COVID-19 crisis. By May 2024 the Committee had undertaken some 520 visits (298 periodic and 222 ad hoc), and had published 472 reports.</p>
                    <p usage="casee">Bosnia and Herzegovina, Czech Republic and Slovenia were included on the CPT’s schedule of periodic visits for 2024.</p>
                    <p usage="eerca">Georgia was included on the CPT’s schedule of periodic visits for 2024.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Framework Convention for the Protection of National Minorities</heading>
                    <p>The Council’s Framework Convention for the Protection of National Minorities entered into force in February 1998, and had been ratified by 39 states at January 2024. Contracting parties are required to submit reports on the implementation of the treaty at regular intervals to an Advisory Committee composed of 18 independent experts. The Committee of Ministers may adopt resolutions based on opinions issued by the Advisory Committee. A European Commission against Racism and Intolerance (ECRI), which became operational in 1994 and was reconstituted in 2004, is an independent human rights monitoring body that analyses and assesses the effectiveness of legal, policy and other measures taken by member states to combat racial hostility and intolerance towards minorities in European societies. It prepares policy recommen­dations and guidelines on issues of importance to combating racism and intolerance, collects and dissem­inates examples of good practices relating to these issues, and also aims to raise awareness of the problems of racism and intolerance among the general public. ECRI was working on a sixth cycle of country monitoring reports during 2019-24.</p>
                    <p>A Co-ordination Meeting on Combating Anti-Muslim Hatred and Discrimination was established in March 2024. In May the Committee of Ministers adopted a Recommendation on combating and recording hate crimes.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Convention on Access to Official Documents</heading>
                    <p>In October 2020 a binding Council of Europe Convention on Access to Official Documents (also referred to as the Tromsø Convention) entered into force, recognizing a general right of citizens’ access to documentation kept by public authorities.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Commissioner for Human Rights</heading>
                    <p>The Council’s Commissioner for Human Rights, whose office was established by a resolution of the Council's Committee of Ministers in May 1999, promotes awareness of and respect for human rights in member states. In 2024 the focus areas of the Commissioner’s human rights activities included: AI; children's rights; counter-terrorism; the ongoing economic crisis; environment; freedom of expression and of the media; lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender and intersex (LGBTI) rights; migration; older persons; persons with disabilities; Roma and travellers; transitional justice; the war in Ukraine; and women’s rights.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading usage="casee">European Programme for Human Rights Education for Legal Professionals (HELP)</heading>
                    <p usage="casee">HELP supports member states with the implementation of the ECHR at national level, by enhancing the capacity of judges, lawyers and prosecutors. HELP in the EU, focusing on the member states that are also members of the EU, is funded by that institution.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Children’s Rights</heading>
                    <p>The Convention on Contact concerning Children entered into force in September 2005 and by January 2024 had been ratified by nine states. A Convention on the Protection of Children against Sexual Exploitation and Sexual Abuse entered into effect in July 2010.</p>
                    <p>In February 2022, in the context of a programme titled `Building a Europe for and with Children’ that was initiated in 2006, the Committee of Ministers endorsed a fourth successive Strategy for the Rights of the Child, to cover the period 2022-27. The Strategy had the following pillars aimed at supporting all children in member states: Freedom from violence; Equal opportunities and social inclusion; Access to safe use of technologies; Child-friendly justice; Giving a voice to every child; and Children’s rights in crisis and emergency situations.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Counter-Trafficking</heading>
                    <p>The Council’s Convention on Action against Trafficking in Human Beings entered into force in February 2008, and by January 2024 had been ratified by 48 countries. Parties to the Convention are monitored by the Group of Experts on Action against Trafficking in Human Beings (GRETA). In October 2013 GRETA urged recognition of the following principles: anti-trafficking efforts should focus on every type of trafficking, for example trafficking for labour exploitation (including forced begging) and for organ removal; the private sector and media should play a greater role in helping to prevent trafficking; and the effectiveness of anti-trafficking measures should be subject to thorough independent assessment. In March 2015 the Council adopted a Convention against Trafficking in Human Organs; this entered into force in March 2018. A fourth round of GRETA evaluation visits and reports, focused on the theme `vulnerabilities to human trafficking’, was initiated in mid-2023.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Rights of Persons with Disabilities</heading>
                    <p>The 1992 Recommendation on a Coherent Policy for People with Disabilities contains the policy principles for the rehabilitation and integration of people with disabilities. This model programme recommends that governments of all member states develop comprehensive and co-ordinated national disability policies that take into account prevention, diagnosis, treatment, education, vocational guidance and training, employment, social integration, social protection, information and research. It has set benchmarks, both nationally and internationally.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Gender Equality</heading>
                    <p>A Council of Europe Gender Equality Commission was inaugurated in June 2012. The Council’s Gender Equality Strategy covering the period 2014-29, which was finalized in March 2024 and was to be formally adopted by a high-level conference to be convened in May, was focused on six priority areas: preventing and combating gender stereotypes and sexism; preventing and combating violence against women and girls, and domestic violence; guaranteeing equal access of women and girls to justice; achieving balanced participation of women and men in political, public, social and economic life; ensuring women’s empowerment and gender equality in relation to global and geopolitical challenges; and achieving gender mainstreaming and including an intersectional approach in all the Council’s policies and measures.</p>
                    <p>In March 2019 the Committee of Ministers issued a Recommendation aimed at halting sexism (the first ever such international legal instrument). The Recommendation emphasized that sexism was a widespread manifestation of `historically unequal power relations’ between women and men, preventing the full advancement of women in society. It stated that the `hegemony of the masculine model’ should not be consecrated in language and communication.</p>
                    <p usage="ewyb edio casee eerca">The binding Council of Europe Convention on Preventing and Combating Violence against Women and Domestic Violence (Istanbul Convention) entered into force on 1 August 2014. In May 2015 a Group of Experts on Action against Violence against Women and Domestic Violence (GREVIO) was established to monitor implementation of the Convention. GREVIO’s membership was expanded in September 2018 from 10 to 15. In March 2021 Turkey (now Türkiye) formally denounced the Istanbul Convention, declaring that the detail of its content was incompatible with the country’s social and family norms and values. The Council of Europe’s Secretary-General deplored the action, and emphasized the importance of the Convention in protecting women and girls. Turkey’s withdrawal was completed on 1 July. Citing similar grounds, in May 2020 the Hungarian legislature had approved a declaration that rejected ratification of the Convention (Hungary being a signatory state, but not a party), and in July of that year the Polish Government also indicated that it would initiate a process of withdrawal. In March 2021 the Polish national legislature voted to present to parliamentary committees for examination draft legislation (titled `Yes to Family; No to Gender’) which would provide for that country’s withdrawal from the Convention. The Istanbul Convention had 38 ratifications as at January 2024 (including the EU, which acceded on 1 October 2023).</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading usage="casee">LGBTI Rights</heading>
                    <p usage="casee">The Council maintains a Compendium of Good Practices on Local and Regional Level Policies to Combat Discrimination on the Grounds of Sexual Orientation and Gender Identity, which has made the following recommendations for local and regional authorities: LGBTI issues should be incorporated into relevant policy areas; the experiences of LGBTI people should be monitored, in respect of their wellbeing and safety; partnerships on LGBTI issues, human rights and anti-discrimination should be fostered with NGOs; local government staff and service providers should be trained on LGBTI issues; information on the specific needs of LGBTI people should be provided; and exchanges of good practice and experience should be promoted.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Migrants’ Rights and Integration</heading>
                    <!--~migrant workers-->
                    <p>The 1983 European Convention on the Legal Status of Migrant Work­ers is based on the principle of equality of treatment for migrant workers and the nationals of the host country as to housing, working conditions and social security. An international con­sultative committee monitors the application of the Convention, which, as at January 2024, had been ratified by 11 states.</p>
                    <p usage="edio casee">A European Agreement on Transfer of Responsibility for Refugees entered into force in December 1980. In May 2006 the Council of Europe adopted a Convention on the avoidance of statelessness in relation to state succession.</p>
                    <p>
          In October 2015 the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="IO-CE.CEDEVTBANK.001">Council of Europe Development Bank (CEB)</xr>
           established a Migrant and Refugee Fund (q.v.), further to the significant migration and refugee crisis that had arisen in that year. In March 2016 the Council of Europe’s Secretary-General emphasized that applications for asylum in European states should be treated on a case-by-case basis without recourse to collective refoulement, within the framework of the ECHR. The Commissioner for Human Rights made a series of recommendations in May 2016 aimed at implementing successfully European standards on migrant integration. These included facilitating family reunion and long-term residency; placing the onus on states to provide free language courses and materials to enable the linguistic and civic integration of migrants; and the provision of equal education, training and employment opportunities to migrants and non-migrants alike. The Commissioner has repeatedly expressed concern over evictions of Roma migrants, rendering them homeless, in several member states. Since 2022 the CEB’s Migrant and Refugee Fund and a dedicated Ukraine Solidarity Fund (established in that year) have provided assistance to countries supporting a massive influx of refugees fleeing the conflict in Ukraine.
        </p>
                    <p usage="casee">In October 2016, in view of reports that some 10,000 minor migrant children were missing on the continent, PACE adopted a resolution on harmonizing the protection of unaccompanied minors in Europe. A further resolution issued by the Assembly in January 2020 emphasized the dangers faced by missing children—including trafficking, exploitation, violence and sexual abuse—and their need for special protection.</p>
                    <p>In March 2023 the Council of Europe and partners launched an Academy on the Integration of Migrants and Refugees in Polish Cities, which was to organize a series of relevant training courses.</p>
                    <p usage="ewyb edio eerca">In April 2024 the Council adopted a €2.8m. response package to support Armenia in integrating a large influx of refugees who had arrived in September 2023 from Nagornyi Karabakh (Azerbaijan).</p>
                    <!--~stateless numbers-->
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading usage="ewyb edio eerca">Prisoners’ Rights</heading>
                    <p usage="ewyb edio eerca">A Council for Penological Cooperation organizes regular high-level conferences of directors of prison administrations and is responsible for collating statistical information on detention and community sanctions in Europe. In April 2022 the Council reported that the member states in 2021 with the highest incarceration rates were Russia (with 328 inmates for every 100,000 inhabitants; Russia left the Council in March 2022), and Türkiye (325 inmates per 100,000 inhabitants).</p>
                    <p usage="ewyb edio">In July 2022 the CPT issued a report on the UK which raised concern over an escalation of prison violence since 2016, including serious inter-prisoner violence and violence perpetrated by prisoners against staff. The report also stated concern over the lack of a coherent strategy to tackle chronic overcrowding in UK prisons, and emphasized the cumulative adverse effects on prisoners of overcrowded poor living conditions and of a lack of purposeful prison regimes.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Roma Rights</heading>
                    <p>In October 2010 a high-level meeting of the Council of Europe adopted the Strasbourg Declaration on Roma, detailing guiding principles and priorities to encourage the empowerment and inclusion of Roma/travellers in Europe (estimated to number 10m.-12m.). In April of that year the Council of Europe joined other partner organizations in establishing an International Task Force for the Education of Roma, aimed at improving the educational situation and social inclusion of Roma, Sinti and travellers. The Council’s seventh Roma Women's Conference was convened in March 2019, in Finland. In July 2020 the Committee of Ministers adopted a Recommendation that called on member states to include Roma/traveller history in school curricula.</p>
               </p-group>
               <!--Jan. 2019 PACE resolution on conflicts raised by the application of Shari`a law, including provisions that contravene the ECHR-->
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO-COE.100" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Democracy and Rule of Law</heading>
               <p>The Council of Europe promotes democratic governance and focuses on fostering sustainable democratic societies. A World Forum for Democracy is normally convened once a year by the Council. The 12th Forum was to take place in Strasbourg, in November 2024, on the theme `Democracy and Diversity—Can we transcend the divides?’.</p>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Reykjavík Principles for Democracy</heading>
                    <p>In May 2023 the fourth summit of the Council adopted a series of 10 Reykjavík Principles for Democracy: (i) the active promotion of democratic participation through free and fair elections, and the encouragement, as appropriate, of deliberative democracy; (ii) the organization of elections and referenda; (iii) the maintenance of independent and effective parliaments and other democratic institutions; (iv) upholding the separation of powers between state institutions; (v) ensuring independent, impartial and effective judiciaries; (vi) combating corruption relentlessly (including through prevention, and pursuing accountability); (vii) safeguarding the right to freedom of expression (including academic and artistic freedom, and enabling a free, independent, plural and diverse media); (viii) investing in a democratic future by ensuring youth participation and education; (ix) supporting a safe enabling environment for civil society and human rights defenders; and (x) enabling equal and meaningful participation in political and public life for women and girls.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Congress of Local and Regional Authorities of the Council of Europe (CLRAE)</heading>
                    <p>The Congress was established in 1994 in order to protect and promote the political, administrative and financial autonomy of local and regional European authorities by encouraging central governments to develop effective local democracy. Annual sessions are mainly concerned with local government matters, regional planning, protection of the environment, town and country planning, and social and cultural affairs. The 40th session of the CLRAE, held online in March 2021, adopted the following strategic priorities for 2021-26: developing effective public health crisis responses; enhancing the quality of representative democracy and citizen participation; reducing inequalities; addressing environmental issues and climate action; and addressing digitalization and AI in a local context.</p>
                    <p usage="edio">The Congress monitors implementation of the European Charter of Local Self-Government, which entered into effect in December 1987, and since 2013 has covered all member states. The Charter outlines common standards for effective local democracy. An Additional Protocol to the European Charter of Local Self-Government, on the right to participate in the affairs of a local authority entered into force in June 2012. Other legislative guidelines for the activities of local authorities and the promotion of democracy at local level include the 1980 European Outline Convention on Transfrontier Co-operation, and its Additional Protocol which was opened for signature in 1995; a Convention on the Participation of Foreigners in Public Life at Local Level (entered into force in 1997); and the European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages (entered into force 1998). In addition, the European Urban Charter (adopted 1992) defines citizens' rights in European towns and cities, for example in the areas of transport, urban architecture, pollution and security; the European Urban Charter II: Manifesto for a new urbanity (adopted in May 2008) updates and complements this in the context of advancing globalization; the Charter on the Participation of Young People in Municipal and Regional Life (adopted in 1992 and revised in 2003) sets out guidelines for encouraging the active involvement of young people in the promotion of social change in their municipality or region; and the Reference Framework on Regional Democracy (adopted in November 2009) outlines principles with regard to the democratic structure, organization, competencies and national context of regional authorities.</p>
                    <p usage="ewyb edio">The Congress aims to promote the principles of local democracy beyond Europe, for example through Euro-Arab dialogue between cities, and through Euro-Mediterranean co-operation. Morocco and Tunisia were granted CLRAE Partner for Local Democracy status in, respectively, April and October 2019.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Venice Commission</heading>
                    <p>
          In May 1990 the Committee of Ministers adopted a Partial Agreement to establish the European Commission for Democracy through Law, based in Venice, Italy (`Venice Commission’). The Commission was enlarged in February 2002 and comprises all Council of Europe member states in addition to Kyrgyzstan (which joined in 2004), Chile (2005), the Republic of Korea (2006), Algeria and Morocco (2007), Israel and Tunisia (2008), Peru and Brazil (2009), Mexico (2010), Kazakhstan (2012), the USA (2013), Costa Rica (2016) and Canada (2019). Belarus became an associate member in October 2010, although its participation was suspended in March 2022. The Commission is composed of independent legal and political experts, mainly senior academics, supreme or constitutional court judges, members of national parliaments, and senior public officers. Its main activity is constitutional assistance and it may supply opinions upon request, made through the Committee of Ministers, by PACE, the Secretary-General or any member states of the Commission. Other states and international organizations may request opinions with the consent of the Committee of Ministers. The Commission is active throughout the constitutional domain, and has worked on issues including legislation on constitutional courts and national minorities, electoral law and other legislation with implications for national democratic institutions. The creation of the Council for Democratic Elections institutionalized co-operation in the area of elections between the Venice Commission, PACE, and the CLRAE. The Commission disseminates its work through the CODICES database and the 
          <i>Bulletin of Constitutional Case-Law</i>
          . In March 2019 the Commission issued a set of 25 Principles for the Protection and Promotion of the Institution of the Ombudsman, also referred to as the Venice Principles.
        </p>
                    <p>The Venice Commission organized the fifth Congress of the World Conference on Constitutional Justice in October 2022, in Bali, Indonesia, on the theme `Constitutional Justice and Peace’. The Congress united regional and linguistically-based groupings of constitutional courts, councils and supreme courts from around the world. (The first Congress had been convened in January 2009.)</p>
                    <p usage="eerca">In March 2014 the Council of Europe Secretary-General requested two urgent opinions from the Venice Commission, concerning: the compatibility with constitutional principles of the decision of the Supreme Council of the Autonomous Republic of Crimea in Ukraine to hold a referendum on becoming a constituent territory of the Russian Federation or restoring Crimea’s constitution of 1992, and on the compatibility with international law of the draft Federal Constitutional Law of the Russian Federation on `Amending the Federal Constitutional Law on the procedure of admission to the Russian Federation and creation of a new subject of the Russian Federation in its composition’. In December 2020, at the request of President Zelensky of Ukraine, the Venice Commission issued two further urgent opinions, which addressed recent anti-corruption legislation and detailed a series of recommendations aimed at strengthening the functioning of Ukraine’s Constitutional Court.</p>
                    <p>In March 2024 the Venice Commission adopted an opinion on the rule of law requirements of amnesties, with particular reference to legislation recently passed in Spain relating to the institutional, political and social normalization of Cataluña (Catalunya).</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>European Committee on Legal Co-operation</heading>
                    <p>The European Committee on Legal Co-operation has the objective of harmonizing among member states and modernizing public and private law, including administrative law and law relating to the judiciary. Areas of focus include lobbying, e-justice, legal aid and standards relating to the detention of migrants.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>European Commission for the Efficiency of Justice (CEPEJ)</heading>
                    <p>The Commission, established in 2002, aims to improve the efficiency and functioning of the justice system of member states, and to enhance implementation of the international legal instruments of the Council of Europe. In December 2018 the CEPEJ adopted a European Ethical Charter on the use of AI in Judicial Systems. The Council of Europe’s Consultative Council of European Judges supports the implementation of a global action plan for judges. In December 2022 the Consultative Council issued an Opinion aimed at guiding judges on means of exercising with restraint their right to freedom and expression, including in the press and social media, without compromising their independence and impartiality in the courtroom.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Committee of Legal Advisers on Public and International Law (CAHDI)</heading>
                    <p>CAHDI, comprising the legal advisers of ministers responsible for foreign affairs of member states and of several observer states, is authorized by the Committee of Ministers to examine questions of public international law, and to exchange and, if appropriate, to co-ordinate the views of member states. CAHDI functions as a European observatory of reservations to international treaties, and also focuses on the immunities of states and international organizations, international criminal justice, and the national implementation of international sanctions measures.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="CE.IO.1009" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Crime and Counter-Terrorism</heading>
               <p>Expert committees and groups operating under the authority of the European Committee on Crime Problems have prepared conventions on such matters as extradition, mutual assistance, recognition and enforcement of foreign judgments, transfer of pro­ceed­ings, suppression of terrorism, transfer of prisoners, compensation payable to victims of violent crime, money laundering, confiscation of proceeds from crime and corruption. During the period 2023-27 the Council’s Committee on Counter-Terrorism was implementing a Counter-Terrorism Strategy that was focused on three pillars of protection, prosecution and prevention. In May 2024 the Committee of Ministers adopted a series of guidelines aimed at strengthening national emergency responses to terrorist attacks.</p>
               <p id="CE.IO.107" usage="ewyb edio">A Criminological Scientific Council, composed of specialists in law, psychology, sociology and related sciences, advises the Committee and organizes crimino­logical research conferences and colloquia. A Council for Police Matters was established in 2002.</p>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Group of States Against Corruption (GRECO)</heading>
                    <p>GRECO, which became oper­ational in 1999, assesses members’ compliance with Council instruments for combating corruption, including the 1999 Criminal Law Convention on Corruption. As at January 2024 GRECO had 50 members, including the USA and Kazakhstan. A fifth round of GRECO evaluations (ongoing in 2024) was initiated in March 2017.</p>
                    <p usage="eerca">In March 2019 GRECO, in its first ever such declaration, designated Belarus as continuously non-compliant with its anti-corruption standards.</p>
                    <p usage="casee">In a report issued in July 2022 GRECO listed 24 recommendations to the Serbian authorities that were aimed at preventing corruption with regard to persons with top executive functions in government.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Select Committee of Experts on the Evaluation of Anti-Money Laundering Measures (MONEYVAL)</heading>
                    <p>
          MONEYVAL is responsible for mutual evaluation of the anti-money laundering measures in place in 28 Council of Europe states that are not members of the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="WB0231XC.IO.TXT.21">Financial Action Task Force</xr>
           (FATF), or else have joined FATF but wish to continue to be evaluated by MONEYVAL. Israel, the Holy See, Gibraltar, and the UK Crown Dependencies of Guernsey, Jersey and the Isle of Man have also joined MONEYVAL. States are evaluated, in accordance with FATF practices and procedures, against the relevant international standards in the legal, financial and law enforcement sectors. In the legal sector this includes the evaluation of states’ obligations under the Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime and on the Financing of Terrorism, which entered into force in May 2008. With effect from 1 January 2011 MONEYVAL was elevated to the status of an independent monitoring mechanism, reporting directly to the Committee of Ministers. The full evaluations of MONEYVAL are confidential, but summaries of adopted reports are made public. A fifth MONEYVAL evaluation round was being undertaken during 2015-24.
        </p>
                    <p usage="casee">Follow-up reports on the effectiveness of new measures introduced in Albania and Slovenia to counter money laundering and the financing of terrorism were published in June 2023.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Convention for the Prevention of Terrorism</heading>
                    <p>The Council of Europe Convention for the Prevention of Terrorism entered into force in June 2007, and had been ratified by 43 member states by January 2024. In April 2018 the Committee of Ministers issued a Recommendation that outlined a series of measures aimed at identifying and addressing the challenges posed by returning terrorist fighters and potential so-called `lone wolf’ terrorists. A new Council of Europe Counter-Terrorism Strategy, covering the period 2023-27, was adopted in February 2023. In April 2021 the Committee of Ministers adopted guidelines on addressing the nexus between terrorist organizations and organized crime groups. A Convention on Offences relating to Cultural Property, which entered into force on 1 April 2022, aimed—within the context of combating terrorism and organized crime—to stem the destruction of and illicit trafficking in cultural property.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="CE.IO.1002" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Education, Culture and Heritage</heading>
               <p>The European Cultural Convention covers education, culture, heritage, sport and youth. Programmes on education, higher education, culture and cultural heri­tage are managed by four steering committees. A Council of Europe cultural governance observatory, CultureWatchEurope, is mandated to monitor the follow up to all relevant Council of Europe Conventions; to act as a forum for the exchange of information on culture, and on cultural and natural heritage; to observe ongoing relevant policies, practices, trends and emerging issues; to highlight good practice; and to analyse and advise on policy.</p>
               <p id="CE.IO.112">
        The education programme comprises projects on education for democratic citizenship and human rights, history teaching, intercultural dialogue, instruments and policies for plurilingualism, the education of European Roma/Gypsy children, teaching remembrance—education for the prevention of crimes against humanity, and the `Pestalozzi' training programme for education professionals. The Council of Europe’s main focus in the field of higher education is the Bologna Process, which was launched in 1999 with the aim of establishing a European Higher Education Area, including education networks and student exchanges at all levels. In April 2009 ministers responsible for higher education in the member countries of the Bologna Process adopted the Budapest-Vienna Declaration officially launching the European Higher Education Area. Other Council of Europe activities in the area of education include the partial agreement for the European Centre for Modern Languages located in Graz, Austria, the Network for School Links and Exchanges, and the European Schools Day competition, organized in co-operation with the EU. In November 2020 the Committee of Ministers established an Observatory on History Teaching in Europe. The Observatory’s first thematic report, titled 
        <publ-name>Pandemics and Natural Disasters as Reflected in History Teaching,</publ-name>
         was prepared in 2022. A second, 
        <publ-name>Economic Crises in History Teaching,</publ-name>
         was to follow in 2024.
      </p>
               <p usage="casee">In October 2015 the Council launched a Pan-European Platform on Ethics, Transparency and Integrity in Education, which aimed to combat corruption in areas including plagiarism, the sale of diplomas, and the misdirection of funds intended for school construction projects.</p>
               <p>In December 2000 the Committee of Ministers adopted a Declaration on Cultural Diversity, which created a framework for a European approach to valuing cultural diversity. The Council’s third summit meeting, convened in Warsaw, in May 2005, identified intercultural dialogue as a means of promoting tolerance and social cohesion; this was supported by the Faro Declaration on the Council of Europe's Strategy for Developing Intercultural Dialogue adopted by ministers responsible for culture convened in Faro, Portugal, in October. In May 2008 a Council of Europe Intercultural Cities Programme was launched, which addressed replacing a multicultural approach to cultural diversity with an intercultural outlook, encouraging interaction between and hybridization of cultures.</p>
               <p usage="casee">In September 2015 member states approved the establishment of a Berlin, Germany-based European Roma Institute for Arts and Culture.</p>
               <p>The Framework Convention on the Value of Cultural Heritage for Society (known as the Faro Framework Convention), which entered into force in June 2011, establishes principles underpinning the use and development of heritage in Europe. In May 2017 a new Convention on Offences relating to Cultural Property was opened for signature, with the aim of combating the illegal looting and trafficking of cultural artefacts. An Enlarged Partial Agreement on Cultural Routes was established in January 2011, and by 2024 had 40 member states and covered 47 routes.</p>
               <p usage="casee">In 2024 the Enlarged Partial Agreement on Cultural Routes included the Iron Curtain Trail, the Hansa Route (which includes Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania and Poland), the European Fairy Tale Route (including Croatia, Greece and Lithuania), the European Route of Jewish Heritage, TRANSROMANICA—The Romanesque Routes of European Heritage (including Romania, Serbia and Slovakia), the European Route of Historic Thermal Towns (including Croatia, the Czech Republic, Greece and Hungary), the Iron Age Danube Route (Bosnia and Herzegovina, Bulgaria, Croatia, Hungary and Slovenia), and the ATRIUM—Architecture of Totalitarian Regimes of the 20th century in Europe's Urban Memory (Albania, Bulgaria, Croatia, Romania).</p>
               <p usage="eerca">In 2024 the Enlarged Partial Agreement on Cultural Routes included the Iron Curtain Trail, the European Route of Jewish Heritage, and the ATRIUM—Architecture of Totalitarian Regimes of the 20th century in Europe's Urban Memory.</p>
               <p>The European Audiovisual Observatory, established in 1992, collates and circulates information on legal, production, marketing and statistical issues relating to the audiovisual industry in Europe, covering film, television, video and DVD, and new media. The European Convention for the Protection of Audiovisual Heritage and its Protocol were opened for signature in November 2001; the first document entered into force in January 2008, and the second in April 2014. The Eurimages support fund, in which 39 member states (and, as an associate member since March 2017, Canada) participate, helps to finance the co-production of films. The Convention for the Protection of the Architectural Heritage and the Protection of the Archaeo­logical Heritage provide a legal framework for European co-operation in these areas. All member states, as well as Belarus, the Holy See and Kazakhstan, have acceded to the European Cultural Convention.</p>
               <p usage="edio">A European Heritage Days event is celebrated annually in September.</p>
               <!--European Heritage Network-->
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="CE.IO.1003" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Environment</heading>
               <p>The Council of Europe Convention on the Conservation of European Wildlife and Natural Habitats (Bern Convention), which entered into force in June 1982, gives total protection to 693 species of plants, 89 mammals, 294 birds, 43 reptiles, 21 amphibians, 115 freshwater fishes, 113 invertebrates and their habitats. The Convention established a network of protected areas known as the Emerald Network; the Network is being developed in partnership with the EU, and has also been extended to Africa (Burkina Faso, Morocco, Senegal and Tunisia). The Council awards the European Diploma for protection of sites of European significance, supervises a network of biogenetic reserves, and co-ordinates conservation action for threatened animals and plants. A European Convention on Landscape entered into force in March 2004, and details an obligation for public authorities to adopt policies and measures at local, regional, national and international level for the protection, management and planning of landscapes. A protocol aimed at opening the Landscape Convention to wider global membership entered into force on 1 July 2021.</p>
               <!-- Conferences of ministers responsible for regional/spatial planning (CEMAT) 17th CEMAT - 2017-->
               <p>The elaboration of a non-binding instrument to address human rights and the environment is pending. In May 2023 the fourth summit of Council of Europe heads of state and of government—stressing the urgency of countering the `triple planetary crisis’ of pollution, climate change, and biodiversity loss—affirmed the interconnection of the environment and human rights, recalling extensive related case law and practice developed by the European Court of Human Rights and the European Committee of Social Rights, and relevant conventions (including the environmental dimension of the Tromsø Convention, recognizing a general right of citizens’ access to documentation kept by public authorities).</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="CE.IO.999" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Health</heading>
               <p>Through a series of expert committees, the Council aims to ensure constant co-operation in Europe in a variety of health-related fields, with particular emphasis on health services and patients' rights. These efforts are supplemented by the training of health personnel. Recommendations adopted by the Committee of Ministers in the area of health cover blood, the role of patients, cancer control, disabilities, health policy development and promotion, health services, the protection of human rights and dignity of persons with mental disorders, the organization of palliative care, transplantation, access to healthcare by vulnerable groups, and the impact of new information technologies.</p>
               <p>
        A Partial Agreement in the Social and Public Health Field aims to protect the consumer from potential health risks connected with commonplace or domestic products, including asbestos, cosmetics, flavouring substances, pesticides, pharmaceuticals and products that have a direct or indirect impact on the human food chain. Two European treaties have been concluded within the framework of this Partial Agreement: the European Agreement on the Restriction of the use of Certain Detergents in Washing and Cleaning Products, and the Convention on the Elaboration of a European Pharmacopoeia (establishing legally binding standards for medicinal substances, auxiliary substances, pharmaceutical preparations, vaccines for human and veterinary use and other articles; by January 2024 the Convention had been ratified by 39 states and by the EU). The World Health Organization, the Taiwan Food and Drug Administration and 30 (European and non-European) states participate as observers in the sessions of the European Pharmacopoeia Commission. In 1994 a procedure on certification of suitability to the 
        <i>European Pharmacopoeia</i>
         monographs for manufacturers of substances for pharmaceutical use was established. A network of official control laboratories for human and veterinary medicines was established in 1995, open to all signatory countries to the Convention and observers at the Phar­macopoeia Commission. The 11th edition of the 
        <i>European Pharmacopoeia</i>
        , in force from 1 January 2023, included 2,474 harmonized European standards, or `mono­graphs', 387 general methods of analysis and 2,870 descriptions of reagents.
      </p>
               <p>Through the Council of Europe’s so-called Pompidou Group 42 states work together, through meetings of ministers, officials and experts, to counteract drug abuse and illicit drug trafficking. (Ukraine joined the Pompidou Group in January 2022.) A revised statute for the Pompidou Group, adopted by the Committee of Ministers in June 2021, extended its mandate to cover new types of addiction (such as internet gambling), and addictive behaviours that are related to tobacco, alcohol and other legal substances. The official name of the Group was amended to reflect its broader mandate, to the Council of Europe International Cooperation Group on Drugs and Addiction. The Group follows a multi­disciplinary approach embracing, in particular, legislation, law enforcement, prevention, treatment, rehabilitation and data collection. It maintains an online register of ongoing drug research projects.</p>
               <p>The Council of Europe Convention on the Counterfeiting of Medical Products and Similar Crimes Involving Threats to Public Health (`Medicrime Convention’) was opened for signature in October 2011 and entered into force in January 2016. By January 2024 the Convention had 23 states parties, including eight non-member states.</p>
               <p>In December 1999 the Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and the Dignity of Human Beings with Respect to the Applications of Biology and Medicine: Convention on Human Rights and Biomedicine (the Oviedo Convention) entered into force, as the first internationally binding legal text to protect people against the misuse of biological and medical advances. The Convention incorporated provisions on scientific research, the principle of informed patient consent, organ and tissue transplants and the prohibition of financial gain from the disposal of a part of the human body. Protocols prohibiting the medical cloning of human beings, concerning the transplantation of human organs and tissue, and on biomedical research entered into force in, respectively, March 2001, May 2006, and September 2007. A further Protocol, concerning genetic testing for health purposes, entered into effect on 1 July 2018. A draft protocol relating to protection of the human embryo and foetus is under development. A Recommendation on xenotransplantation (i.e. the transplantation of organs between diverse species) was adopted by the Committee of Ministers in 2003. In April 2018 the Council of Europe published a guide to implementing the principle of prohibition of financial gain with respect to the human body and its parts (from both living and deceased donors). A five-year Council of Europe strategy on human rights and biomedical technologies was introduced in June 2020, with a focus on strengthening governance of technologies and equity in healthcare provision, and on placing a high value on physical and mental integrity.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="CE.IO.1000" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Media and Digital Technologies</heading>
               <p>Implementation of the Council of Europe's work programme concerning the media is undertaken by the Steering Committee on Media and Information Society, which was established in January 2012. Policy and legal instruments have been developed on subjects including exclusivity rights; media concentrations and transparency of media ownership; protection of journalists in situations of conflict and tension; inde­pendence of public service broadcasting, protection of rights holders; legal protection of encrypted television services; media and elections; protection of journalists' sources of information; the independence and functions of broadcasting regulatory authorities; and coverage of legal proceedings by the media. The Council has developed several international binding legal instruments, including the European Convention on Transfrontier Television (adopted in 1989), the European Convention Relating to Questions on Copyright Law and Neighbouring Rights in the Context of Transfrontier Broadcasting by Satellite (1994), and the European Convention on the Legal Protection of Services Based on or Consisting of Conditional Access (2001).</p>
               <p>The Council is engaged with internet governance, standard setting, and with balancing citizens’ fundamental right to privacy and data protection against the free flow of personal data through the internet and the centralization of personal records. A Council of Europe Digital Partnership aims to support governments in drafting internet policy.</p>
               <p>The Convention for the Protection of Individuals with regard to Automatic Processing of Personal Data (referred to as Convention 108) entered into force in October 1985, and had been ratified by 55 states at January 2024 (including eight non-European states—Argentina, Cabo Verde, Mauritius, Mexico, Morocco, Senegal, Tunisia and Uruguay). In July 2004 an Additional Protocol to Convention 108, concerning supervisory authorities and transborder data flows, entered into force. In May 2018 the Committee of Ministers adopted a further Protocol to Convention 108 that provided for updated effective safeguards to protect privacy in the context of transborder data flows through the internet. (The new Protocol was referenced by the EU’s landmark General Data Protection Regulation, which became legally binding and fully applicable in all EU member states on 25 May.) By January 2024 the Protocol had 31 ratifications (including non-member states Argentina, Mauritius and Uruguay). Convention 108 is regarded as a cornerstone of privacy legislation in Europe, and also as a global standard. The Convention’s monitoring committee has given consideration to the development of technologies such as biometric identification, smart cards and video surveillance, and has, accordingly, produced guidelines on the application of data protection principles in respect to these techniques. Furthermore, the potential for linking state databases with those of other agencies, such as insurance companies and banks, has been a priority area of focus. In March 2019 the Council adopted a Recommendation aimed at ensuring respect for the human rights to privacy and data protection when processing citizens’ health-related personal data. In October 2020 the Council issued a report that cited privacy and personal data protection weaknesses in the context of digital contact tracing measures that had been implemented by Convention 108 states parties to contain the spread of COVID-19. The report noted that such digital tracing systems were not broadly harmonized between countries. New guidelines were released in January 2023 on the human rights-focused management of personal data in national digital identity systems.</p>
               <p>A Convention on Cybercrime (the Budapest Convention) entered into force in July 2004 and by January 2024 had 69 states parties (including 24 non-member states). In 2003 member states concluded an additional Protocol to the Convention relating to the criminalization of acts of a racist and xenophobic nature committed through computer systems. A second additional Protocol, focused on enhancing law enforcement authorities’ cross-border access to data (including in the digital `cloud’), was adopted by the Committee of Ministers in November 2021; this was opened for signature in May 2022 and required five ratifications to enter into force (it had received two as at January 2024). In July 2019 the Cybercrime Convention Committee adopted a Guidance Note aimed at facilitating criminal justice measures against attempts to interfere in elections through malicious cyber activities. A set of guidelines covering the use of information and communication technologies during electoral processes was adopted by the Council of Ministers in February 2022. The Council of Europe organizes a so-called Octopus Conference on Cybercrime every 12-18 months, to bring together cybercrime experts from academia, the private sector and international organizations (most recently in December 2023, in Bucharest, Romania). </p>
               <p>In April 2015 the Council initiated, with partners including the International Federation of Journalists, the internet-based Platform to Promote the Protection of Journalism and Safety of Journalists. In April 2016 the Committee of Ministers issued a Recommendation that encouraged member states to review national legislation and practice concerning media freedom, with a view to ensuring that this conformed to the provisions of the European Convention of Human Rights. The Council of Europe analyses case law relating to maintaining a fair balance between the criminalization of defamation and the maintenance of freedom of expression. In March 2024 the Platform stated concern over the unlawful deployment of spyware and abusive lawsuits against journalists.</p>
               <p>In February 2022 the Committee of Ministers adopted new guidelines on the use of information and communication technologies in electoral processes.</p>
               <p>The inaugural meeting was convened in January 2022 of an AI Co-ordination Group (CAI), tasked with harmonizing work relating to AI across all sectors of the organization. Meanwhile, an intergovernmental committee of representatives of member states, 11 non-member states and the private sector, academia and civil society, undertook to draft a Council of Europe Framework Convention on AI. The Convention, establishing principles and obligations throughout all stages of the design, development and use of AI systems, was finalized in mid-March 2024, and adopted by the Committee of Ministers in May. It was to be opened for signature from 5 September.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="CE.IO.1004" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Sport</heading>
               <p>The Committee for the Development of Sport, founded in 1977, oversees sports co-operation and development on a pan-European basis, bringing together all the states parties to the European Cultural Convention. Its activities focus on the implementation of the European Sport Charter and Code of Sports Ethics (adopted in 1992 and revised in 2001), the role of sport in society, and the practice of both recreational and high-level sport. A Charter on Sport for Disabled Persons was adopted in 1986. The Committee also prepares the Conferences of European Ministers responsible for Sport (usually held every four years) and has been responsible for drafting two important conventions to combat negative influences on sport. The European Convention on Spectator Violence and Misbehaviour at Sport Events (1985) provides governments with practical measures to ensure crowd security and safety, particularly at football matches. The Anti-Doping Convention (1989), regulating drug testing procedures, had been ratified by 52 countries as at January 2024, including (non-member states) Australia, Belarus, Canada, Morocco, Russia and Tunisia. An Annex to the Convention, listing prohibited substances and methods, is updated annually. In May 2007 the Committee of Ministers adopted the Enlarged Partial Agreement on Sport (EPAS), which aimed to develop a framework for a pan-European platform of intergovernmental sports co-operation and to set international standards. By 2024 EPAS had 39 member states. A Convention on an integrated safety, security and service approach at football matches and other sports events, adopted by the Committee of Ministers in May 2016, was opened for signature in July; it entered into force on 1 November 2017. A Convention on the Manipulation of Sports Competitions entered into force on 1 September 2019.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="CE.IO.1005" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Youth</heading>
               <p usage="casee">In 1972 the Council of Europe established the European Youth Centre (EYC) in Strasbourg. A second residential centre was created in Budapest, Hungary, in 1995. The centres, run with and by international non-governmental youth organizations representing a wide range of interests, provide about 50 residential courses a year (study sessions, training courses, symposia).</p>
               <p>The European Youth Foundation (EYF) aims to provide fi­nancial assistance to European activities of non-governmental youth organizations and began operations in 1973. Since that time more than 300,000 young people have benefited directly from EYF-supported activities. The Steering Committee for Youth conducts research in youth-related matters and prepares for ministerial conferences. In 1997 the Council of Europe and the European Youth Information and Counselling Agency (EYRICA) concluded a partnership agreement on developing the training of youth information workers. In November 2004 the EYRICA General Assembly adopted a European Youth Information Charter, which is accessible in 32 European languages. In 2009 Principles for Online Youth Information were added to the Charter. The Charter and Principles were updated in 2018.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="CE.IO.597" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>External Relations</heading>
               <p id="CE.IO.123" usage="ewyb edio">Israel, Canada and Mexico are represented in PACE by observer delegations, and certain European and other non-member countries participate in or send observers to certain meetings of technical committees and specialized conferences at intergovernmental level. Full observer status with the Council was granted to the USA in 1995, to Canada and Japan in 1996 and to Mexico in 1999. The Holy See has had a similar status since 1970.</p>
               <p usage="ewyb edio">In October 2023 the Council’s Secretary-General stated condemnation in the strongest terms for the terrorist attacks perpetrated by Islamic militants on Israeli territory. She welcomed government action within Europe to `block the path of extremists on all sides’, with a view to preventing the exportation of the Middle East conflict to European societies. She also called on Israel to protect civilian populations during its military response.</p>
               <p usage="ewyb edio">During 2023-25 the Council of Europe was implementing the EU-funded South Programme V, which aimed to promote democracy in the southern Mediterranean area, and encouraged southern Mediterranean states to join Council of Europe networks and conventions.</p>
               <!--~ Nagorno-Karabakh-->
               <p>A European Centre for Global Interdependence and Soli­darity (the `North-South Centre') was established in Lisbon, Portugal, in 1990. The Centre is co-managed by parliamentarians, governments, NGOs and local and regional authorities. Its activities cover: public information and media relations; edu­cation and training for global interdependence; and dialogue for global partnership. In March 2024 the Centre and South Programme V co-launched a Rule of Law Youth Network (RoLYN).</p>
               <p>The EUR-OPA Major Hazards Agreement, adopted in 1987, and open to non-member states, facilitates co-operation between European and non-European southern Mediterranean countries, covering knowledge of hazards, risk prevention, risk management, post-crisis analysis and rehabilitation. By 2024 there were 22 parties to the Agreement, including Lebanon and Morocco.</p>
               <p usage="casee">In January 2011 PACE issued a report that made several allegations concerning war crimes, crimes against humanity and other crimes believed to have been committed in Kosovo. The EU established a Special Investigative Task Force to investigate associated evidence, leading to the establishment in 2015 of a Kosovo Specialist Chambers and Specialist Prosecutor's Office, with jurisdiction over the alleged crimes. The sixth meeting of a Council of Europe-Kosovo working group took place in October 2021. (The inaugural meeting had been held in November 2013.) In March 2019 the Council of Europe initiated the project Improving the Protection of European Human Rights Standards by the Constitutional Court of Kosovo. In May 2022 Kosovo applied to join the Council of Europe, and in April 2023 the Ministerial Committee voted (with 33 votes in favour, seven against, and five abstentions) to refer the application to PACE for consideration. In April 2024 PACE recommended that Kosovo should be invited to become a Council member, and that Kosovo’s fulfilment with effect from its accession of a series of commitments and obligations should be monitored. A final decision was to be taken by the Committee of Ministers.</p>
               <p-group>
                    <heading usage="edio ewyb eerca">Relations with Belarus</heading>
                    <p usage="edio ewyb eerca">In April 2021 PACE urged Belarus to introduce comprehensive electoral reforms, in order to align its systems with international standards. In late May PACE’s General Rapporteur on Media Freedom and the Safety of Journalists stated grave concern at the forced diversion by the Belarusian authorities of international passenger flight FR4978 to that country’s capital, Minsk, and removal from the aircraft and arrest of a Belarusian journalist, Raman Pratasyevich, and of his Russian companion. He called for their immediate release. (Pratasyevich, had played a prominent role in reporting on protests against Belarus’s President Alyaksandr Lukashenka.)</p>
                    <p usage="edio ewyb eerca">In March 2022 the Council’s Committee of Ministers determined to suspend all relations with Belarus as a result of its active support of Russia’s invasion of Ukraine in the previous month. In November a Council of Europe Contact Group on Belarus initiated a meetings process with Belarusian opposition representation. In February 2023 the Council’s Secretary-General initiated a 15-point action plan aimed at supporting civil society and opposition representatives working towards a free, democratic future for Belarus. In the following month the Council and partners convened a workshop to support Belarusian journalists in exile.</p>
                    <p usage="edio ewyb eerca">In January 2024 PACE agreed a broad set of proposals on which to build a democratic future for Belarus; approved a representative delegation of `Belarusian democratic forces’; and determined to appoint a General Rapporteur for a Democratic Belarus. The President of PACE termed legislative and local elections that were held in that country in February `a travesty of democracy’.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading usage="ewyb edio eerca">Relations with Georgia</heading>
                    <p usage="ewyb edio eerca">In May 2024 the Council of Europe’s Secretary-General stated deep concern over the ongoing passage through Georgia’s legislature of a controversial draft law `on transparency of foreign influence’, which was not deemed compatible with European democratic and human rights standards. She urged Georgia’s parliamentarians to wait for a forthcoming opinion of the Council’s Venice Commission prior to making any final decisions on the matter.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading usage="ewyb edio eerca">Relations with Russia</heading>
                    <p usage="ewyb edio eerca">In February 2022 Russia’s rights of representation in the Council were suspended by the Committee of Ministers following its military invasion of Ukraine. On 16 March, in accordance with an Opinion adopted by an extraordinary session of PACE on the previous day, Russia’s membership of the Council and of its various partial agreements, was rescinded with immediate effect. (Russia’s voting rights in PACE had previously been revoked during 2014-19 following its recognition of the independence of the hitherto Ukrainian autonomous territory of Crimea.)</p>
                    <p usage="ewyb edio eerca">
          In January 2021 the European Court of Human Rights ruled that Russia had held de facto control over Crimea since 27 February 2014, and in January 2023 it determined that Russia had usurped de facto control of separatist areas of eastern Ukraine from 11 May 2014—thus establishing the Court’s jurisdiction with respect to cases that had been brought against Russia by Ukraine and the Netherlands (relating, 
          <i>inter alia,</i>
           to the shooting down in July 2014 from Ukrainian airspace of Malaysia Airlines flight MH17).
        </p>
                    <p usage="eerca">In September 2021 the European Court of Human Rights ruled that the Russian authorities had been responsible for the assassination by poisoning in 2006, in the UK, of Aleksandr Litvinenko (a former Russian security agent who had sought asylum in the UK). The case had been brought by Litvinenko’s widow. The Russian authorities were deemed not to have conducted an effective domestic investigation into ascertaining accountability for the murder.</p>
                    <p usage="edio ewyb eerca">In February 2021 the Secretary-General and PACE President jointly stated deep regret at the detention (to serve a term of imprisonment relating to a conviction imposed in October 2017) of Aleksei Navalnyi—a Russian opposition leader who had recently recovered, in Germany, from (according to the German authorities) poisoning with the nerve agent Novichok, and had then returned voluntarily to Russia. They jointly emphasized that the European Court of Human Rights had found the 2017 conviction to have been arbitrary and unreasonable.</p>
                    <p usage="edio ewyb eerca">In early 2023 the Council of Europe’s Secretary-General reminded Russia of its legal obligation to implement 2,404 judgments issued by the European Court of Human Rights to which it remained bound. In March the PACE leadership held discussions with representatives of Russia’s opposition democratic forces, to explore paths for future co-operation. Also in that month, the Committee of Ministers issued a statement deploring the continuing detention of Navalnyi, reportedly mainly in solitary confinement without adequate access to legal representation. In May the President of the Committee of Ministers, Secretary-General, PACE President, President of the CLRAE, and Commissioner for Human Rights issued a joint declaration in which they condemned escalating repression within Russia of critics of that country’s regime, including the recent conviction (related to his criticism of the war against Ukraine), and sentencing to a 25-year term of imprisonment, of Vladimir Kara-Murza, a journalist and politician. In August PACE’s General Rapporteur for political prisoners condemned the conviction of Aleksei Navalnyi on further (extremism-related) charges, and the imposition on him of a further sentence, of 19 years. In mid-March 2024 the Committee of Ministers strongly condemned the Russian authorities with regard to Navalnyi’s death in February in detention, and demanded an independent international investigation into the circumstances. PACE adopted a resolution in April that declared the Russian state fully responsible for Navalnyi’s death, and proposed a series of measures aimed at combating the `totalitarian regime’ of Russia’s President Putin.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="CE.IO.CE-EU.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF" usage="casee eerca">
               <heading usage="casee eerca">Joint Council of Europe-EU Initiatives</heading>
               <p usage="casee">In May 2016 the Council of Europe and the EU signed an agreement establishing a joint Horizontal Facility for the Western Balkans, with a focus on justice and on the protection of fundamental rights, equality, and of freedom of expression and of the media. A second programming phase of the Facility, covering the period 2019-22, commenced in May 2019 with funding of €41m.</p>
               <p usage="casee">Over the period 1 January 2020-30 June 2023 the Council of Europe and EU jointly implemented the iPROCEEDS-2 initiative in South-East Europe and Türkiye, with a focus on strengthening co-operation in combating cybercrime through targeting crime proceeds accrued on the internet.</p>
               <p usage="eerca">In 2020 the Council of Europe and the EU initiated a four-year Central Asia Rule of Law Programme, with a focus on reinforcing democracy, human rights and rule of law in Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan.</p>
          </int-org-section>
     </int-org-section>
     <int-org-section id="CE.IO.598" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Finance</heading>
          <p id="CE.IO.127">The budget is financed by contributions from members on a proportional scale of assessment (using population and gross domestic product as common indicators). In 2024 it totalled €624.6m.</p>
     </int-org-section>
