                    <found-date>April 1956 as the Council of Europe Resettlement Fund, subsequently renamed as the Council of Europe Social Development Fund, with the present name adopted in Nov. 1999</found-date>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">a multilateral development bank with a social development mandate</content-note>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">grants loans for investment projects with a social purpose and contributing to strengthening cohesion in Europe, including job creation and preservation in small and medium-sized enterprises; social housing; improving urban living conditions; health and education infrastructure; managing the environment; and supporting public infrastructure. A Human Rights Trust Account (f. in 2008) finances technical projects in the field of human rights protection</content-note>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">by March 2024, since its inception in Oct. 2015, grants totalling €35m. had been approved under the Bank’s Migrant and Refugee Fund</content-note>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">in April 2022 a CEB Green Social Investment Fund was initiated</content-note>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">a Ukraine Solidarity Fund was launched in that year, to support Ukrainian refugees and host states</content-note>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">in April and June two social inclusion bonds were issued to boost the Ukraine refugee crisis response</content-note>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">in Dec. an overall capital increase of a maximum of €4,250m. was approved, to raise the Bank’s subscribed capital from €5,480m. to €9,730m.; a Strategic Framework covering the period 2023-27 was also introduced, taking into account new challenges, including the repercussions of the Ukraine conflict</content-note>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">in July 2023, following Ukraine’s accession to the Bank, a first €2m. grant was approved for that country, to support the rehabilitation of war-damaged homes</content-note>
                    <content-note style="NORMAL">the total value of new projects approved in 2022 was €4,244m.</content-note>
